message_1:
Solve the system of linear equations using QR decomposition:

\begin{align*}
2x+y+z &= 9\\
4x+6y+2z &= 30\\
-2x+4y+3z &=4
\end{align*}

message_2:
To solve the system of linear equations using QR decomposition, we first need to write the system in matrix form Ax = b, where A is the matrix of coefficients, x is the column vector of variables, and b is the column vector of constants.

The given system of linear equations can be written in matrix form as:

A = \begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 & 1\\
4 & 6 & 2\\
-2 & 4 & 3
\end{bmatrix}

x = \begin{bmatrix}
x\\
y\\
z
\end{bmatrix}

b = \begin{bmatrix}
9\\
30\\
4
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we need to perform QR decomposition on matrix A, which means we need to find orthogonal matrix Q and upper triangular matrix R such that A = QR.

Using the Gram-Schmidt process, we can find the orthogonal matrix Q and upper triangular matrix R:

Q = \begin{bmatrix}
0.333 & -0.182 & 0.925\\
0.667 & -0.546 & -0.308\\
-0.333 & 0.818 & 0.308
\end{bmatrix}

R = \begin{bmatrix}
6 & 6 & 2\\
0 & 4.36 & 2.18\\
0 & 0 & 1.54
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we can solve the system Rx = Qtb:

Qt = \begin{bmatrix}
0.333 & 0.667 & -0.333\\
-0.182 & -0.546 & 0.818\\
0.925 & -0.308 & 0.308
\end{bmatrix}

Qt * b = \begin{bmatrix}
15\\
-12.36\\
2.31
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we have the following system of linear equations:

\begin{align*}
6x + 6y + 2z &= 15\\
4.36y + 2.18z &= -12.36\\
1.54z &= 2.31
\end{align*}

Solving this system using back-substitution, we get:

z = 2.31 / 1.54 ≈ 1.5

y = (-12.36 - 2.18 * 1.5) / 4.36 ≈ 2

x = (15 - 6 * 2 - 2 * 1.5) / 6 ≈ 1

So, the solution to the system of linear equations is:

x ≈ 1, y ≈ 2, z ≈ 1.5
